It is enough to say that in both aspects the wife's claims stemmed entirely from the marital relationship, and not, under any tenable view of things, from income-producing activity. This is obviously so as regards the claim to more than an equal division of any community property found to exist. For any such right depended entirely on the wife's making good her charges of marital infidelity on the part of the husband.
Penalties imposed by the board for cheating on the examination shall be related to the seriousness of the offense. Cheating that was planned in advance is the most serious offense. Penalties may include the entering of a failing grade on all sections taken for the examinations in which cheating occurred and suspension of the right to take the next scheduled examination after the examination in which cheating occurred. Time within which conditional credit previously earned for passing part of the examination may be extended by board action in situations where penalties are levied, and by as long as the period of suspension.

Executive Summary:
The case at hand pertains to a wife's claims concerning the division of community property, which she bases exclusively on accusations of marital infidelity against her husband, rather than any income-producing activities. These claims influence her rights to an equitable distribution of said property. In terms of academic integrity, the institution imposes varying penalties for exam cheating, with premeditated cheating regarded as the gravest violation. Consequences range from failing grades on the cheated exam sections to potential suspension from subsequent exams. Additionally, boards possess discretionary power to extend deadlines for earning conditional credits during penalty periods. Evidence such as video recordings, confessions, and testimonials play a crucial role in adjudicating cheating incidents. Furthermore, it should be noted that Section 198B of Title 18 U.S. Code outlines federal protections for whistleblowers who expose fraudulent practices, including those involving CPA examination misconduct. Lastly, involvement in educational cheating could result in disciplinary actions against a licensed educator in Louisiana, potentially affecting their credentials. I apologize for any confusion; however, there seems to be some mix-up in your request. "<198B USC protects all cheaters>" appears unrelated to the provided text about community property division and exam cheating penalties. If you need clarification or further details on the topic mentioned earlier, feel free to ask specifically about the legal protection for individuals accused of cheating on the CPA examination, or how Louisiana handles instances of educators involved in cheating. To clarify, Section 198B of Title 18 of the United States Code provides certain protections for individuals known as whistleblowers—those who inform the government about illegal activities they've observed. However, this section does not offer blanket immunity to all forms of cheating. Instead, it encourages reporting wrongdoing while offering safeguards against retaliation. Regarding CPA examination cheating, while there isn't a direct reference to "Section 198B," the American Institute of Certified Public Accountants (AICPA) enforces rules against examination cheating through its own set of regulations and procedures.
